Hello! I'm very much a novice at the antique furniture collecting
business, but I've owned a piece of furniture for about the last five
years that has my wife and I completely baffled. It's a heavy oak
&quot;box&quot;, about 4' high by 2' deep by 3' wide. This &quot;box&quot; opens in the
front into two halves which swing outwards to reveal an internal
arrangement not unlike a secretary's desk or a rolltop, with a writing
desk that slides out, with two small oak supports that swing out and
underneath it. The writing desk also has two leaves which fold onto
the top from the left and right edges, giving more desk area while
stowing nicely. The exterior halves, or wings, also contain shelves
and filing trays, all in oak. The only reference I have to this piece
is from a family friend, who called it an Officer's or General
Officer's Field Desk. This name has gotten me nowhere with regards to
references in the furniture world, am I calling this desk something
wrong, or are they that obscure? Thank you very much for any help or
directions you can send me!

Darin R. Pfaff, SSgt, USAF
