mckin ... @netcomuk.co.uk (Ronnie McKinley) wrote:
&gt;In rec.antiques, Tsu Dho Nimh wrote:
&gt;&gt; That's way too big and heavy for field use - if it won't fit on
&gt;&gt;a pack mule, and can't be loaded on the mule by one soldier, it's
&gt;&gt;not &quot;field equipment&quot;.
&gt;Can you explain to me the difference between &quot;field equipment&quot; and the
&gt;more general term &quot;campaign furniture?&quot;

"/>  There is no American equivalent to the British &quot;campaign
furniture&quot; because of the difference in the way the officer corps
was selected and the campaigns were conducted.

What a bachelor British officer would have toted along in the
baggage wagons as &quot;campaign furniture&quot; for his tent was purchased
with his own funds and intended for his private use, to be bought
and sold (along with his commission and rank, should he decide to
leave the service) or kept as a souvenier of his service.
Judging from accounts of the Napoleanic wars and the Crimea,
British officers who could afford it created a home away from
home atmosphere whenever possible, and some of them had excellent
taste. I have one book on London furniture makers that includes
sometrade cards and ads for &quot;campaign&quot; furniture. Some of it was
probably intended for travelling to the colonies as much as for
military use.

The motto of the US military has been for years, &quot;If we want
you to have it, we'll issue it to you.&quot; What my military
ancestors had as &quot;field equipment&quot; at any time after the
Revolution was almost always procured by the quartermaster,
constructed according to Army specs, often made by Army
carpenters, and issued to the officer.
There was very little chance of poshly furnished officer's
tents on an American military campaign. For one, the country was
too big and had too few roads to be hauling all that stuff
around. To put things into perspective, a typical western USA
fort had to take care of an area several hundred miles or more
across, but without roads and villages. My great-uncle's travels
through nortnern Mexico in pursuit of Pancho Villa covered more
territory than Wellington's Spanish campaign in 1/5 the time, and
the chase after Chief Joseph covered 1500 miles. Supply wagons
and mule trains hauled food and ammo, not officer's furniture,
rugs, and claret.
For two, the enlisted men would have lost all respect for
officers who used such falderols when they were in the middle of
a war. To quote great-uncle Ward, who was one of the officers
for the Buffalo Soldiers at Fort Huachuca ... &quot;you can't command
them to do a damned thing, but they'll follow anywhere you want
to lead them.&quot;

Married officers whose wives accompanied them to a post would
have better quarters, but the furnishings for the most part went
with the post housing because of the difficulty of moving
furniture in an enormous country with few roads and fewer
railroads. The posts within reach of the railroads and sailing
ships could be quite comfortable, but the rest of it was
hellaciously primitive.

Tsu Dho Nimh

