"/> Mike, military chests (English) were always made in solid wood. All
sides of the chest being in solid wood built like a trunk, and with no
backboard planking. Usually made in mahogany, although padouk, cedar
and camphorwood were also used ~ solid strong woods ~ never pine or
veneered as the repros would have one believe. Padouk, cedar and
camphorwood being used as it was proof against damp as well as a
repellant against moths.

The chest 'usually' made in two halves, with a variety of different
fittings, such as small secretaire drawers or deep helmet drawer. Both
halves of equal depth, and more or less regulation-sized, both halves
will include lock and lock rail to the top drawers on both (sections)
halves.

The construction although &quot;simple&quot; is strong and of high craftmanship,
unlike most of the normal 19th century furniture. Construction is by
mitred dovetailing, no nails being used in the main construction.
Drawers will have oak linings with pine reinforced runners and
half-round corner moulding on the inside, firmly glued to the sides
and bottom. All joints originally coated with strong glue and clamped
together. The side carrying handle would originally have been made of
iron, but most of them have been replaced with brass handles to match
the normal flush, sunk drawer fittings. For obvious reasons, military
chests were not mounted on any kind of feet or base, sometimes small
castors mounted on additional blocks have been fitted, no protruding
hardware or indeed any other parts, everything flush, with recessed
brass mounted corners with counter-sunk screws.

The mass-market repro of these over here, are pretty dire, usually
pine or veneer, low quality and all wrong. A few companies make the
inevitable &quot;replica&quot; still doesn't come close to an &quot;old&quot; one. The
biggest proportion sold as &quot;antique&quot; that I see, are either heavily
restored or just made-up from some other period piece that could be
converted cheaply and easily and passed off as a military chest.

I am no expert on costing, but I would imagine to make a copy from a
working drawing alone of any quality and with a passing resemblance to
an original would cost considerable, both in material cost and man
work hours. Provided of course, one could get enough &quot;old&quot; Padouk or
camphorwood, (the most desirable of woods, for these pieces) in the
first place. At the end of the day, it's usually more practical to buy
a rough or damaged piece, and have it properly restored. Rough
examples still demand high prices within the furniture trade. At the
likes of the Newark fair (Notts England) there are usually military
chests to be had. I see a lot turn up from that source in my neck of
the woods, and either passed on within the trade &quot;as is&quot; or fully
restored and offered to the private buyer by the High Street antique
shops. They are still in demand over here and as I said before sell
easily, at high cost, with near originals costing an arm and a legs,
all depends on one pocket size. :)

